{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18436"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18436"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60183"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7762"},{"type":"tags","id":"7764"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25868"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is investigating pain scores in two groups of patients following different surgical procedures. The pain scores are measured on a scale of 1-10. Initial analysis shows the data is not normally distributed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statistical tests would be most appropriate to compare the pain scores between these two groups?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paired t-test","Independent t-test","Analysis of variance","Pearson correlation coefficient","Mann-Whitney U test"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EMann-Whitney U test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice because it is a non-parametric test designed to compare two independent groups when data is not normally distributed or when dealing with ordinal data like pain scores. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this test analyses the ranks of the data rather than the actual values, it is therefore suitable for both non-normal distributions and ordinal data like pain scores. It tests whether one group tends to have higher or lower values than the other group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll of the other options\u003C/strong\u003E are parametric tests that require normally distributed data. Parametric tests tend to be more powerful when their assumptions are met but can give misleading results when they are violated. Non-parametric tests make fewer assumptions about the underlying distribution and are more robust, though generally less powerful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Mann-Whitney U test is used to compare two independent groups when data is not normally distributed or ordinal.","Non-parametric tests make fewer assumptions about data distribution compared to parametric tests.","The Mann-Whitney U test analyses ranks rather than actual values, making it suitable for ordinal data."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18436"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api